<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How do I convert roof pitch to degrees?", answer: "Take the pitch as a fraction (rise / 12) and apply arctangent: angle = atan(rise/12). Common conversions: 3/12 = 14.04°, 4/12 = 18.43°, 6/12 = 26.57°, 8/12 = 33.69°, 10/12 = 39.81°, 12/12 = 45°. The calculator does this conversion automatically from any of three input methods." },
  { question: "What is the difference between pitch and slope?", answer: "In roofing, pitch is typically written as rise-per-12 (for example, 6/12). Slope is the same number but expressed as a fraction, ratio, or angle. Grade is the slope expressed as a percentage — a 6/12 pitch is a 50% grade. All three describe the same physical steepness; pitch is the convention for residential roof framing." },
  { question: "What is the minimum roof pitch for shingles?", answer: "Asphalt shingles require a minimum pitch of 2/12 per manufacturer warranties, and most manufacturers recommend 4/12 for best performance. Between 2/12 and 4/12, you must install a double layer of underlayment or a self-adhering ice-and-water shield membrane over the entire deck. Below 2/12, use a membrane roof system (TPO, EPDM) rather than shingles." },
  { question: "What is a standard residential roof pitch?", answer: "Most suburban homes use a 4/12, 6/12, or 8/12 pitch. 4/12 is common for ranch homes, 6/12 is the most popular for traditional styles, and 8/12 to 12/12 is typical for colonials, Cape Cods, and Tudor-style roofs. The right pitch depends on climate (steeper sheds snow better), style, attic use, and local codes." },
  { question: "How do I measure pitch on an existing roof?", answer: "Place a 12-inch level horizontally against the roof surface (indoors on the rafter or outdoors on the sheathing). Hold it level, and measure the vertical distance from the far end of the level to the roof surface — that is the rise. If the rise is 6 inches, the pitch is 6/12. You can also use a smartphone level app or a dedicated pitch finder." }
]) %>

